    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-10-19T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-10-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="399"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d399">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 (E. W.)/11–742: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Algiers (<persName type="from"
                            >Cole</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">War Department</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="94" xml:id="d399fn1">Copy supplied by the Office of the Secretary of
                        Defense under cover of letter of September 7, 1960.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Algiers</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-10-19">October 19,
                            1942</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>No. 694. From Murphy. Vice Consul Reid learns from good source at Casablanca of
                    the interception of a message from German Armistice Commission recommending the
                    immediate occupation of French Morocco and estimating that four armored
                    divisions would be required for the task. This is along the lines of other
                    messages said to have been sent by the German Consul General at Casablanca
                    urging German military intervention in French Morocco. [Murphy.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cole</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
